member.name: T:Keen.VRage.Input.GameInputProcessorComponent
member.summary: Input processor designed for games.

remarks.para: In the Game Input Processor active input is fed to s. When those controls activate the actions mapped to them via the active are selected for processing.

Active actions are propagated to the input stack from top to bottom. At each level the active input context is allowed to process all candidate actions it defines to handle, any actions that share inputs with the actions activated at a given level are discarded. Remaining unhandled actions are passed on to the next layer.

member.name: P:Keen.VRage.Input.InputActionDefinition.Reactivate
member.summary: Allow controls bound to this action to reactivate immediately when a context changes.

remarks.para: It usually makes sense to set this option to true for actions bound to a pointer control.

Normally when an is deactivated it will hold on to any controls that were previously captured by it. The context will get an instant notification the control was cancelled, but the control will stay active internally and block other input until it deactivates.

To the user this means that if a control were bound to a key then it will stay active while the user holds down the key, even if the input context that was processing an action bound to that control is deactivated.
Setting this option to true will instead force the control to immediately re-activate, as if the user had let go of the keys for a split second, when the context is deactivated.
